Post-Hoc Tests and a Fractional FST

Author
Affiliation
Rodney J. Dyer

Center for Environmental Studies
Virginia Commonwealth University
Richmond, Virginia 23284, USA

Published

September 27, 2022

Abstract

The estimation of population-level genetic structure is a fundamental task for evoluationary, landscape, and ecological genetics. Strucure statistics quantify the relative partitiioning of total genetic variance into one or more nested levels. These fundamental parameters provides insights into historical and ongoing microevolutionary processes and as such has spawned a large family of estimatorsâsome unique and some repetitive. What is lacking is a post hoc interpreation of these structure statistics. Simply rejecting the null hypothesis of no structure says little about how genetic variation is distributed within and among sampled strata. Here the parameter \(\Delta_S\) is defined, yielding a stratum-level comparison of relative contribution to overall structure which aids in interpreting the way in which population structure is distributed rather than the magnitude of overall structure.

Introduction

The analysis of population genetic structure is commonly estimated from one (or more) paramaters which can be traced back to Wrights \(F_{ST}\).

Despite the introduction of the population genetic parameter \(\theta\) by Weir and Cockerham (1984) as an extension of the more common parametric analysis of variance, parameters estimated for population genetic structure often ignore the similarities. Excoffier, Smouse, and Quattro (1992) â and Smouse and Peakall (1999) â extended the single locus treatment to be additive across loci.

To draw an analogy between the analysis of population genetic structure and normal parametric statistics, rejecting the null hypothesis that there is no genetic structure is tantamount to finding a significant \(F\) statistic in an analysis of variance. In fact, (Dyer et al. 2004) showed that the single locus \(\theta\) statistic (Weir and Cockerham 1984) and its multilocus analog \(\Phi_{ST}\) (Excoffier, Smouse, and Quattro 1992) are just edge cases of a more general set of linear regression models operating as Q-modeâthe covariance matrix is among \(N\) individualsârather than the more common R-mode, where the covariance matrix is based upon the differences among \(p\) variables.

In all but the most simple of population genetic studies, the immediate next step in parametric statistics is to conduct a post hoc test to determine which treatment levels are contributing to this finding, whereas in population genetics the route of action is to either simply interpret the magnitude of the structure statistic in relation to other published organisms whose life-history traits are similar or to conduct a pair-wise analysis of all possible combinations of strata. The former approach is largely a practice of hand-waving due to the fact that numerous different demographic and genetic histories may lead to a similar level of average among-population genetic structure. Moreover, the latter suffers from significant loss in actual statistical powerâwe rarely sample enough individuals within individual locales when conducting analyses of multiple sampling strata yielding large variation around all of our parameters when each of the \(K*(K-1)/2\) pairs of locales.

If our studies are focused on answering if there is genetic structure, we are justified at stopping here. However, if the focus of the work is to characterize how variation is distributed across the landscape rather than if there is structure, then we need to proceed further in understanding the contributions each stratum provides to the amount of observed variation.

In this manuscript, I provide a decomposition of single and multilocus genetic structure whose aim is to understand how genetic variance is distributed. In doing so, this extends the more prosaic approach to just asking if there is structure (e.g., \(F_{ST} > 0\)) allowing the researcher to understand the relative contributions to observed genetic structure by individual strata.

The Geometry of Genetic Structure Statistics

For a single level analysis of structure, the statistic of interest estimates the proportion of the total genetic variance that can be attributable to individuals being assigned to distinct strata. If considering only a single locus of genotypes, this parameter is called \(\theta\) (Weir and Cockerham 1984), whereas if it is additive across loci, it is defined as \(\Phi_{ST}\) (Excoffier, Smouse, and Quattro 1992)âa single locus \(\Phi_{ST}\) is numerically identical to the \(\theta\).

\[ \begin{align} \tag{1} \Phi_{ST} = \frac{\sigma_A}{\sigma_A + \sigma_W} \end{align} \tag{1}\]

These components can be estimated using a geometric interpretation of allelic space as defined by Smouse and Peakall (1999). As a default, the distances between genotypes with a single allelic difference is assigned a unit length. Geometrically, two diploid genotypes can be embedded in a tetrahedron with homozygotes on the vertices and heterozygotes located at the midpoint of each edge (FigureÂ 1). With four vertices, all combinations of two diploid genotypes may be configured and the squared genetic distance can be estimated.

Across all possible combinations of alleles at two diploid genotypes, the pairwise genetic distance, \(\delta_{ij}^2\) is shown in Table @tbl-amovaDistance. Multilocus estimates of genetic distance are derived by summing equally across loci. Individual locus weights can be added in this configuration, though doing so has rarely been shown to be more informative than equal contributions for each locus with the additive effects of multilocus treatments dominating information content.

Across all sampled individuals, we can construct the pair-wise genetic distance matrix, \(\mathbf{D}\) as:

\[ D = \left[ \begin{array}{cccc} 0 & \delta_{12}^2 & \cdots & \delta_{1N}^2 \\ \delta_{21}^2 & 0 & \cdots & \delta_{2N}^2 \\ \vdots & \vdots & \ddots & \vdots \\ \delta_{N1} & \delta_{N2} & \cdots & \delta_{NN}^2 \end{array} \right] \]

where \(\delta_{ij}^2\) represents the squared genetic distance between the \(i^{th}\) and \(j^{th}\) individuals. By definition, the elements of \(\mathbf{D}\) are constrained such that \(\delta_{ii} = 0\) and \(\delta_{ij} \ge 0\). Configured such that individuals are sorted by sampling stratum, this matrix has a distinct block form, which is informative for identifying the compartments within the matrix that represent genetic distances measured both among and with strata. The sum of these squared distances subsets (hereafter \(SSD_{level}\)) can be directly injected into a normal random-effects Analysis of Variance (see Dyer et al. 2004 for a more generalized derivation into general linear models).

The pair-wise distance matrix \(\mathbf{D}\) can be converted into a covariance matrix, \(\mathbf{C}\), whose elements (\(c_{ij}\)) are estimated by

\[ c_{ij} = -0.5( \delta_{ij}^2 -* \delta_{i.}^2 - \delta_{.j}^2 + \delta_{..}^2) \]

where the dot subscripts represent the summation of row and/or column (after Gower (1966)).

Once converted to an R-mode covariance matrix (see Dyer et al. (2004)), the variance decomposition proceeds as from a matrix approach as follows. First, we must define the hypothesis matrix, \(\mathbf{X}\) representing the the row-wise binary allocation of each individual into one of the \(K\) sampled strata represented as columns (see RA and DW (1992)).

\[\begin{align} \mathbf{X} = \left[ \begin{array}{cccc} 1 & 0 & \cdots & 0 \\ 1 & 0 & \cdots & 0 \\ \vdots & \vdots & \vdots & \vdots \\ 0 & 0 & \cdots & 1 \\ 0 & 0 & \cdots & 1 \end{array} \right] \end{align}\]

From this, the an idempotent hypothesis matrix is given as:

\[ \mathbf{H} = \mathbf{X}(\mathbf{X}\mathbf{X}^\prime)^{-1}\mathbf{X} \]

which allows the estimation of the expected pair-wise covariance (or model) matrix, \(\hat{\mathbf{Y}}\) as.

\[ \hat{\mathbf{Y}} = \mathbf{H}\mathbf{C} \]

The residual variance/covariance matrix is thus defined as:

\[ \mathbf{R} = (\mathbf{I}-\mathbf{H})\mathbf{C} \]

Each of these outer-product matrices represent the variance/covariance structure for a single-level decomposition. The total sums of squares (with \(N-1\) degrees of freedom) is estimated by the trace of the total covariance matrix,

\[ SSD_{Total} = tr(\mathbf{C}) \]

The among strata (or model) sum of squared deviations with \(K-1\) degrees of freedom is:

\[ SSD_{Model} = tr(\hat{\mathbf{Y}}) \]

And the residual (error) sums of squares is with \(N - K - 1\) degrees of freedom are:

\[ SSD_{Error} = tr(\mathbf{R}) \]

Each of which are standardized into Mean Squares by division of the appropriate degrees of freedom.

Variance component estimation follows a traditional random effects model because the sampling locales are a subset of potential strata where the organisms exist (see S. R. Searle (1997b)). The expectation of the Mean Squares for the error term is an unbiased estimator of the within strata variance component.

\[ E[MS_{Error}] = \sigma_W^2 \]

but the among strata component is given by solving for \(\sigma_A^2\) from

\[ E[MS_{Among}] = \sigma_A^2 \nu + \sigma_W^2 \]

where \(\nu\) is a coefficient based upon the harmonic mean stratum population size (n.b., the formula for this originally presented for a distance-based approach for estimating population genetic structure in Excoffier, Smouse, and Quattro (1992) has a typo in it, yielding an incorrect value. See S. R. Searle (1997a) instead).

These variance components are additive in that

\[ \sigma_T^2 = \sigma_A^2 + \sigma_W^2 \]which provides direct estimation of the overall magnitude of genetic differentiation (in EquationÂ 1 above). The parameter estimate of \(\Phi_{ST}\) and the significance associated with the of the null hypothesis \(H_O: \sigma_A^2 = 0\) is commonly found by permuting individuals across strata and interpretation of the results are based upon the operation or lack-thereof of microevolutionary processes. However either a rejection or failure to reject this null hypothesis is often where the inferences end, perhaps prematurely, without considering how our sampled strata individually contribute to the parameter \(\sigma_A^2\).

Proportional Contribution of Each Stratum

The within stratum, or error, variance (\(\sigma_W^2\)) is easily decomposed into its additive parts as:

\[\begin{align} \sigma_W^2 &= MSW \\ &= \frac{SSD_{Error}}{df_{Error}} \\ &= \frac{1}{N-K-1}(SSD_1 + SSD_2 + \cdots + SSD_K) \\ &= \frac{1}{N-K-1} \sum_{i=1}^N\frac{\sum_{j=1}^{n_i}\sum_{j=1}^{n_i}\delta_{jk}^2}{2n_i} \end{align}\]

which yields \(K\) distinct estimates of error variance for each of the stratum.

The among component of genetic variation estimated by \(\sigma_A^2\), can be similarly decomposed as.

\[\begin{align} \sigma_A^2 &= \frac{1}{\nu}(MSA - \sigma_W^2) \\ &= \frac{1}{\nu} \left[ \frac{SSD_{Among}}{K-1} - \sigma_W^2 \right] \\ &= \frac{1}{\nu} \left[ \left( \sum_{i=1}^K \sum_{j \ne i}^K \frac{ \sum_{k=1}^{n_j}\sum_{l=1}^{n_j} \delta_{kl}^2}{n_i + n_j} \right) - \sigma_W^2 \right] \\ \end{align}\]

where the double sum can be defined as the standardized amount of sums of squares contributed to the estimation of \(\sigma_A^2\) by the differences between the \(i^{th}\) and \(j^{th}\)populations, which I will define as \(\Delta_{ij}\) for our purposes herein. For simplicity,

Significance Testing

Since we have no single parameter, significance testing is unwaranted. However, we can get an idea of the confidence around each of the \(K\) observations for \(\Delta_S\) by sub-sampling.
